the standard linked list implementation in base/linked_list.jl looks like this:
```mutable struct InvasiveLinkedList{T}
    # Invasive list requires that T have a field `.next &gt;: U{T, Nothing}` and `.queue &gt;: U{ILL{T}, Nothing}`
    head::Union{T, Nothing}
    tail::Union{T, Nothing}
    InvasiveLinkedList{T}() where {T} = new{T}(nothing, nothing)
end```
Since head and tail aren't concrete types, is this going to incur a performance penalty when accessing those fields or is this a case where you can rely on compiler optimizations (union splitting?) to make it still as fast as if head and tail were just ::T ?

